{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619472"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16557"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16557"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0,0.88,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9248"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9248"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60487"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3133"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6614"},{"type":"tags","id":"7162"},{"type":"tags","id":"10434"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21914"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient presents with sudden onset visual field deficits. Clinical examination reveals a contralateral homonymous hemianopia and memory disturbances. The affected blood vessel supplies the occipital lobe and inferior temporal lobe.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arteries is most likely occluded?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Middle cerebral artery","Anterior cerebral artery","Posterior cerebral artery","Pontine arteries","Anterior choroidal artery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the occipital lobe (visual cortex), inferior temporal lobe, and parts of the medial temporal lobe including the hippocampus. Occlusion causes contralateral homonymous hemianopia due to damage to the primary visual cortex, and memory disturbances due to involvement of temporal lobe structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiddle cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the lateral surface of the cerebral hemisphere and would cause different symptoms including hemiparesis and aphasia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere and would affect leg movement and behavior\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPontine arteries\u003C/strong\u003E supply the pons and would cause cranial nerve deficits and motor symptoms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior choroidal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies parts of the internal capsule and would primarily cause motor deficits\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of visual field deficits and memory disturbance is characteristic of posterior cerebral artery territory infarction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The posterior cerebral artery supplies the occipital lobe, inferior temporal lobe, and parts of the medial temporal lobe including the hippocampus.","Occlusion of the posterior cerebral artery causes contralateral homonymous hemianopia due to damage to the primary visual cortex.","Memory disturbances can occur with posterior cerebral artery occlusion due to involvement of the hippocampus and temporal lobe structures."],"references":["Go S. Posterior Circulation Ischemic Stroke. Mo Med. 2015 May-Jun;112(3):192-6. PMID: 26168589; PMCID: PMC6170115.","Kuybu O, Tadi P, Dossani RH. Posterior Cerebral Artery Stroke. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30335329.","Mehndiratta M, Pandey S, Nayak R, Alam A. Posterior circulation ischemic stroke-clinical characteristics, risk factors, and subtypes in a north Indian population: a prospective study. Neurohospitalist. 2012 Apr;2(2):46-50. doi: 10.1177/1941874412438902. PMID: 23983863; PMCID: PMC3745183.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60487"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16557"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60487"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T13:15:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T14:04:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9248"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74981"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https:/